You do not need AI to do this yet. You need a simple analysis.

For each subject, prepare these six tables.

Table 1: Top Tested Topics
Rank	Topic	Number of Questions	Years Appeared
Table 2: Top Theory Areas
Topic	Number of Theory Questions	Estimated Marks	Common Command Words
Table 3: Objective vs Theory
Topic	OBJ	Theory	Advice
Table 4: Repeated Concepts in Different Forms
Concept	Past Question Forms	Student Lesson
Table 5: SSCE–UTME Overlap
Topic	SSCE	UTME	Why Start Early
Table 6: Must-Master List for SS2
Subject	Must-Master Topics	Must-Master Skills
These tables alone can give you a strong seminar.

What is most helpful to their studies?
For students, the most helpful insights are:

Which topics appear most often.

Which topics appear in theory.

Which topics appear in both SSCE and UTME.

Which topics require early practice.

How WAEC rephrases the same idea.

How to understand theory command words.

How to revise topic-by-topic instead of randomly.

For teachers, the most helpful insights are:

Where to focus revision.

How to assign Prep50 topic-by-topic.

Which theory areas need written practice.

Which topics should begin in SS2, not SS3.

How to use past questions as teaching data, not just exam practice.

For school owners/principals, the most helpful insights are:

Why early SS2 preparation improves outcomes.

Why structured materials matter.

How Prep50 can support school-wide exam planning.

How WAEC and UTME preparation can be linked.

Why adopting Prep50 earlier can reduce exam panic.

How to rename the seminar theme now
Since objective traps and capsules are not ready, avoid using them in the theme.

Instead of:

WAEC Question Patterns, Theory Skills, Objective Traps, and the SS2 Advantage

Use:

WAEC Question Patterns, Theory Demands, Repeated Concepts, and the SS2 Advantage

This is more honest and still strong.

Final version:

Prep50 SSCE Exam Insights Seminar
Theme:

WAEC Question Patterns, Theory Demands, Repeated Concepts, and the SS2 Advantage

This fits what you can currently prove from your database.

The strongest insight for marketing
The most powerful message is not just:

“More than 70% of WAEC questions are already in Prep50.”

The stronger message is:

“WAEC does not ask random questions. It repeats topics, concepts, skills, and theory demands. Prep50 helps students see those patterns early and prepare topic by topic before exam pressure begins.”

That is more credible, more academic, and more useful.

It also protects you from sounding like you are claiming to predict WAEC questions.

So the event should not say:

“We know what WAEC will set.”

It should say:

“We have studied what WAEC keeps testing, and we can show students how to prepare intelligently from SS2.”

